sec.p:
It should be noted again that the thruster efficiency is calculated from the rf power Prf\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$P_{rf}$$\end{document} from the rf generator; hence it does not take the solenoid power and the power loss at the rf generator into account. The solenoids can be partially replaced by permanent magnets as investigated in previous studies60–62. Furthermore, developments of rf systems for the thrusters have also been progressed such as efficient switching-type rf generators63,64 and compact frequency-tunable impedance matching techniques65,66. The system developments providing less power losses at the solenoids and the rf generator, reducing the system size, and improving the controllability, remains further challenging issues toward a flight model of the MN rf plasma thruster.

Even if no electrode is exposed to the plasmas, the insulator source wall will be sputtered when the energy of the ions impinging the wall exceeds the threshold of the sputtering as being a crucial problem in the Hall effect thrusters, where the accelerated ions having an energy close to the discharge voltage would be the major factor for the wall erosion67. The ions impinging the source wall in the MN rf plasma thruster is only accelerated by a sheath at the wall, which has a voltage of about 5.2Te\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$5.2T_e$$\end{document} for argon68. As discussed by Del Valle et al., the threshold energy of the sputtering for a quartz glass, being about 35 eV, is close to the typical sheath voltage in the low-pressure rf discharge69. Therefore, the wall erosion induced by the sputtering will be minimized by choosing the wall materials properly and by reducing the electron temperature near the wall (i.e., the sheath voltage). The lifetime of the MN rf plasma thruster has not been verified yet and remains further development issue.

After confirming a stable equilibrium position of the thrust balance (t∼\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$t \sim $$\end{document} 0–27 s), both the solenoid currents (IBup\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$I_{Bup}$$\end{document} and IBdown\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$I_{Bdown}$$\end{document}) are simultaneously turned on (at t∼\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$t\sim $$\end{document}27 s in Fig. 7), where a rapid increase in the amplitude of the pendulum motion and slight change in the equilibrium position can be seen for t∼\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
